article.headline: San Francisco 70, Monmouth (N.J.) 66
article.story: SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- A 3-point shot by senior point guard Armando Surratt broke a tie to help the University of San Francisco win its home opener 70-66 over Monmouth. Surratt's 3-pointer came with 3:08 remaining in the 61-61 game, and the Dons (1-1) kept the lead the rest of the way. Down 53-43 midway through the second half, Monmouth (0-1) rallied on the back of Dejan Delic, who led the Hawks with a career-best 28 points. The junior forward from Serbia-Montenegro scored 16 of the Hawks' 18 points to turn that double-digit deficit to a 61-59 Monmouth lead with 4:13 remaining. Surratt followed his big basket with a driving three-point play to give USF a four-point lead. The Hawks trimmed it to 67-66 on Chris Kenney's 3-pointer with 55 seconds remaining, but never scored again as the Dons made their free throws down the stretch. Dommanic Ingerson led the USF scorers with 18 points, while Jerome Gumbs finished with 15 and Surratt added 14. For USF coach Jesse Evans, it was career win No. 150, with all but 18 of them coming with Louisiana-Lafayette before the 2004-05 season. Dons senior forward Johnny Dukes scored two quick baskets in two minutes early off the bench, but broke his foot, according to Evans, and left the court on crutches at halftime. USF is back in action Wednesday at Stanford. The Hawks next play Thursday against Southern Illinois in the Great Alaska Shootout.
